Question: Followed an abdomen (stomach) injury
Information: Go to Guideline: Abdominal Injury (Adult)

Question: Passed out (i.e., lost consciousness, collapsed and was not responding)
Information: R/O: shock.  FIRST AID: Lie down with the feet elevated.

Question:
[1] Vomiting AND [2] contains red blood or black ("coffee ground") material 
 (Exception: few red streaks in vomit that only happened once)
Information: R/O: gastritis, peptic ulcer disease, Mallory-Weiss tear

Question: [1] SEVERE pain (e.g., excruciating) AND [2] present > 1 hour
Information: R/O: appendicitis or other acute abdomen

Question: [1] MILD-MODERATE pain AND [2] constant AND [3] present > 2 hours
Information: R/O: appendicitis or other acute abdomen

Question: Patient sounds very sick or weak to the triager
Information: Reason: Severe acute illness or serious complication suspected.

Question: Fever > 103 F (39.4 C)
[1] Pain in the scrotum or testicle AND [2] present > 1 hour
Information: R/O: testicular torsion, kidney stone

Question: [1] Fever > 100.0 F (37.8 C) AND [2] diabetes mellitus or weak immune system (e.g., HIV positive, cancer chemo, splenectomy, organ transplant, chronic steroids)
[1] Fever > 100.0 F (37.8 C) AND [2] bedridden (e.g., nursing home patient, CVA, chronic illness, recovering from surgery)
Information: Reason: higher risk of bacterial infection

Question: [1] Fever > 101 F (38.3 C) AND [2] age > 60 years
[1] Vomiting AND [2] contains bile (green color)
Information: R/O: intestinal obstruction

Question: Abdominal pain is a chronic symptom (recurrent or ongoing AND present > 4 weeks)
Information: R/O: irritable bowel syndrome

Question: White of the eyes have turned yellow (i.e., jaundice)
Information: R/O: cholelithiasis, hepatitis

Question: Pain is mainly in upper abdomen  (if needed ask: "is it mainly above the belly button?")
Information: Go to Guideline: Abdominal Pain - Upper (Adult)

Question: Age > 60 years
Information: Reason: higher risk of serious cause of abdominal pain

Question: [1] Unable to urinate (or only a few drops) > 4 hours AND [2] bladder feels very full (e.g., palpable bladder or strong urge to urinate)
Information: R/O: urinary retention

Question: Blood in bowel movements  (Exception: Blood on surface of BM with constipation)
Information: R/O: gastritis, peptic ulcer disease

Question: Black or tarry bowel movements (Exception: chronic-unchanged black-grey bowel movements AND is taking iron pills or Pepto-bismol)
Information: R/O: gastritis, peptic ulcer disease

Question: [1] SEVERE pain AND [2] age > 60 years
Information: Reason: higher risk of serious cause of abdominal pain

Question: Blood in urine (red, pink, or tea-colored)
Information: R/O: kidney stone, UTI, urinary retention

Question: Serious injury with multiple fractures (broken bones)
[1] Major bleeding (e.g., actively dripping or spurting) AND [2] can't be stopped
Information: FIRST AID: Apply direct pressure to the entire wound with a clean cloth.

Question: Wound looks infected
Information: Go to Guideline: Wound Infection (Adult)

Question: Toe injury is main concern
Information: Go to Guideline: Toe Injury (Adult)

Question: [1] Bleeding AND [2] won't stop after 10 minutes of direct pressure (using correct technique)
Information: Reason: may need laceration repair (e.g., sutures)

Question: Skin is split open or gaping (or length > 1/2 inch or 12 mm)
Information: Reason: may need laceration repair (e.g., sutures)

Question: Looks like a dislocated joint (very crooked or deformed)
Information: Reason: If dislocated, adult will be unable to walk at all. Possible vascular compromise. Needs reduction.

Question: Sounds like a serious injury to the triager
Information: R/O: fracture, dislocation

Question: Can't stand (bear weight) or walk
Information: R/O: fracture

Question: Suspicious history for the injury
Information: R/O: domestic violence, elder or vulnerable adult abuse

Question: [1] SEVERE pain AND [2] not improved 2 hours after pain medicine/ice packs
Information: R/O: fracture

Question: Large swelling or bruise (> 2 inches or 5 cm)
Information: R/O: minor fracture, muscle hematoma

Question: [1] Limp when walking AND [2] due to a twisted ankle or foot
Information: R/O: sprain, minor fracture

Question: [1] Last tetanus shot > 5 years ago AND [2] DIRTY cut or scrape
Information: Reason: may need a tetanus booster shot (vaccine).

Question: [1] After 2 weeks AND [2] still painful or swollen
[1] After 3 days AND [2] pain not improved
Information: R/O: sprain, fracture

Question: Small cut (scratch) or abrasion (scrape) is also present
Information: Reason: Minor superficial cut or abrasion.

Question: Minor injury or pain from direct blow or crushing injury
Information: Reason: probably a minor contusion (bruise)

Question: [1] Minor injury or pain from twisting or over-stretching AND [2] walks normally
Information: Reason: probably a minor sprain

Question: Caused by an animal bite
Information: Go to Guideline: Animal Bite (Adult)

Question: Bullet wound, stabbed by knife, or other serious penetrating wound
Information: FIRST AID: If penetrating object still in place, don't remove it (Reason: removal could increase bleeding).

Question: [1] Dirt in the wound AND [2] not removed with 15 minutes of scrubbing
Information: Reason: needs irrigation and/or additional wound care

Question: Puncture wound of foot
Information: Go to Guideline: Puncture Wound (Adult)

Question: [1] Diabetes mellitus AND [2] minor cut or scrape
Information: Reason: increased risk of infection or ulcer

Question: [1] Limp when walking AND [2] due to a direct blow or crushing injury
Information: R/O: contusion, minor fracture

Question: [1] High-risk adult (e.g., age > 60 years, osteoporosis, chronic steroid use) AND [2] limping
Information: Reason: there is greater risk of fracture in patients with osteoporosis (bone thinning)

Question: Diabetes mellitus (Exception: small cut or scrape)
Information: Reason: diabetic neuropathy reduces pain of fracture

Question: Shock suspected (e.g., cold/pale/clammy skin, too weak to stand, low BP, rapid pulse)
Information: R/O: shock.  FIRST AID: Lie down with the feet elevated.

Question: Difficult to awaken or acting confused (e.g., disoriented, slurred speech)
Information: R/O: shock.  FIRST AID: Lie down with the feet elevated.

Question: [1] Blood in stool AND [2] without diarrhea
Information: Go to Guideline: Rectal Bleeding (Adult)

Question: Vomiting also present and worse than the diarrhea
Information: Go to Guideline: Vomiting (Adult)

Question: [1] Blood in the stool AND [2] moderate or large amount of blood
Information: R/O: severe Shigella, Salmonella, Campylobacter or E. coli 0157

Question: Abdominal pain  (Exception: Pain clears with each passage of diarrhea stool)
Information: R/O: bacterial diarrhea

Question: [1] SEVERE diarrhea (e.g., 7 or more times / day more than normal) AND [2] present > 24 hours (1 day)
Information: Reason:  higher risk of dehydration

Question: Fever > 101 F (38.3 C)
Information: R/O: bacterial diarrhea

Question: [1] Mucus or pus in stool AND [2] present > 2 days AND [3] diarrhea is more than mild
Information: R/O: bacterial diarrhea

Question:
[1] Blood in the stool AND [2] small amount of blood
   (Exception: only on toilet paper. Reason: diarrhea can cause rectal irritation with blood on wiping)
Information: R/O: bacterial diarrhea

Question: [1] MILD diarrhea (e.g., 1-3 or more stools than normal in past 24 hours) without known cause AND [2] present >  7 days
Information: R/O: bacterial cause or Giardia

Question: Diarrhea is a chronic symptom (recurrent or ongoing AND present > 4 weeks)
MILD-MODERATE diarrhea (e.g., 1-6 times / day more than normal)
Information: Reason: new or transient diarrhea without significant risk factors; may respond to homecare measures. R/O: viral gastroenteritis

Question: [1] Recent antibiotic therapy (i.e., within last 2 months) AND [2] diarrhea present > 3 days since antibiotic was stopped
Information: R/O: C. difficile diarrhea

Question: [1] Drinking very little AND [2] dehydration suspected (e.g., no urine > 12 hours, very dry mouth, very lightheaded)
Information: Reason: may need IV hydration

Question: Patient sounds very sick or weak to the triager
Information: Reason: Severe acute illness or serious complication suspected.

Question: [1] SEVERE abdominal pain (e.g., excruciating) AND [2] present > 1 hour
Information: R/O: appendicitis or other acute abdomen

Question: [1] SEVERE abdominal pain AND [2] age > 60 years
Information: Reason: higher risk of serious cause of abdominal pain, e.g. mesenteric ischemia

Question: Black or tarry bowel movements (Exception: chronic-unchanged black-grey bowel movements AND is taking iron pills or Pepto-Bismol)
Information: R/O: gastritis, peptic ulcer disease

Question: [1] Fever > 103 F (39.4 C) AND [2] not able to get the fever down using Fever Care Advice
[1] MODERATE diarrhea (e.g., 4-6 times / day more than normal) AND [2] age > 70 years
Information: Reason: higher risk of dehydration and morbidity

Question: Weak immune system (e.g., HIV positive, cancer chemo, splenectomy, organ transplant, chronic steroids)
Information: Reason: broader range of causes

Question: Travel to a foreign country in past month
Information: Reason: Antibiotic therapy may be indicated for the treatment of Traveler's Diarrhea.

Question: [1] MODERATE diarrhea (e.g., 4-6 times / day more than normal) AND [2] present > 48 hours (2 days)
Information: Reason:  higher risk of dehydration

Question: [1] Constant abdominal pain AND [2] present > 2 hours
Information: R/O: diverticulitis, appendicitis or other acute abdomen

Question: Shock suspected (e.g., cold/pale/clammy skin, too weak to stand, low BP, rapid pulse)
Information: R/O: shock.  FIRST AID: Lie down with the feet elevated.

Question: Difficult to awaken or acting confused (e.g., disoriented, slurred speech)
Information: R/O: shock.  FIRST AID: Lie down with the feet elevated.

Question: Chest pain
Information: Go to Guideline: Chest Pain (Adult) first - then use Abdominal Pain guideline.

Question: Tube feedings (e.g., nasogastric, g-tube, j-tube)
Information: R/O: osmotic diarrhea

Question: [1] Vomiting AND [2] abdomen looks much more swollen than usual
Information: R/O: intestinal obstruction

Question: Amputation
Information: FIRST AID: Apply direct pressure to the entire wound with a clean cloth.

Question: Blood glucose > 400 mg/dL (22.2 mmol/L)
Information: Reason: significant hyperglycemia

Question: Unconscious or difficult to awaken
Information: R/O: diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA), severe hyperglycemia, profound hypoglycemia

Question: Acting confused (e.g., disoriented, slurred speech)
Information: R/O: DKA, severe hyperglycemia, hypoglycemia

Question: [1] Blood glucose > 240 mg/dL (13.3 mmol/L) AND [2] vomiting AND [3] unable to check for ketones (in blood or urine)
Information: R/O: DKA. Note: Most people with diabetes who use insulin do the urine ketone test. Others check their blood for ketones using a hand-held device.

Question: Urine ketones moderate - large (or blood ketones > 1.4 mmol/L)
Information: Reason: obtain PCP input regarding medication adjustment and diet

Question: [1] Blood glucose > 240 mg/dL (13.3 mmol/L) AND [2] urine ketones moderate-large (or more than 1+)
Information: R/O: DKA. Note: Most people with diabetes who use insulin do the urine ketone test.

Question: Vomiting lasts > 4 hours
Information: R/O: DKA, dehydration

Question: [1] Vomiting AND [2] signs of dehydration (e.g., very dry mouth, lightheaded, dark urine)
Information: Reason: may need IV hydration, possible DKA

Question: Patient sounds very sick or weak to the triager
Information: Reason: Severe acute illness or serious complication suspected.

Question: [1] Blood glucose > 240 mg/dL (13.3 mmol/L) AND [2] rapid breathing
Information: R/O: DKA

Question: Fever > 100.4 F (38.0 C)
Information: Reason: diabetes suppresses the immune system, consider possibility of bacterial infection

Question: Very weak (e.g., can't stand)
Information: R/O: DKA, severe hyperglycemia, hypoglycemia

Question: Sick day rules for people with diabetes who use insulin, questions about
Sick day rules for people with diabetes who do not use insulin, questions about
[1] Symptoms of high blood sugar (e.g., frequent urination, weak, weight loss) AND [2] not able to test blood glucose
[1] Blood glucose 240 - 300 mg/dL (13.3 - 16.7 mmol/L) AND [2] uses insulin (e.g., insulin-dependent, all people with type 1 diabetes)
Information: Reason: hyperglycemia

Question: [1] Blood glucose > 300 mg/dL (16.7 mmol/L) AND [2] two or more times in a row
Information: Reason: obtain PCP input regarding medication adjustment and diet

Question: [1] Caller has NON-URGENT medication or insulin pump question AND [2] triager unable to answer question
Blood glucose 70-240 mg/dL (3.9 -13.3 mmol/L)
Blood glucose > 500 mg/dL (27.8 mmol/L)
[1] Blood glucose 240 - 300 mg/dL (13.3 - 16.7 mmol/L) AND [2] does not  use insulin (e.g., not insulin-dependent; most people with type 2 diabetes)
Information: Reason: hyperglycemia
